{{multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal | header = | image1 = Rowland resonant transformer.jpg | caption1 = [[Henry Augustus Rowland|Henry Rowland's]] 1889 spark-excited resonant transformer,<ref name="Thomson" /> a predecessor to the Tesla coil.<ref name="Strong" /> | width1 = 218 | image2 = Tesla drawing 1899 - Evolution of Tesla transformer.png | caption2 = Steps in Tesla's development of the Tesla transformer around 1891.<ref name="Tesla1899" /> (1) Closed-core transformers used at low frequencies, (2-7) rearranging windings for lower losses, (8) removed iron core, (9) partial core, (10-11) final conical Tesla transformer, (12-13) Tesla coil circuits | width2 = 260 | footer = }}
[[Nikola Tesla]] patented the '''[[Tesla coil]]''' circuit on April 25, 1891.<ref name="Denicolai1">[http://www.saunalahti.fi/dncmrc1/lthesis.pdf Denicolai, 2001, ''Tesla Transformer for Experimentation and Research'', Ch.1, p. 1-6]</ref><ref name="US_Patent_454622">U.S. Patent No. 454,622, Nikola Tesla, ''[http://www.google.com/patents/US454622 SYSTEM OF ELECTRIC LIGHTING]'', filed 25 April 1891; granted 23 June 1891</ref> and first publicly demonstrated it May 20, 1891 in his lecture "''Experiments with Alternate Currents of Very High Frequency and Their Application to Methods of Artificial Illumination''" before the [[American Institute of Electrical Engineers]] at [[Columbia University|Columbia College]], New York.<ref name="Martin1">The lecture "''Experiments with Alternate Currents of Very High Frequency and Their Application to Methods of Artificial Illumination''" is reprinted in {{cite book | last1 = Martin | first1 = Thomas Cummerford | title = The Inventions, Researches and Writings of Nikola Tesla: With Special Reference to His Work in Polyphase Currents and High Potential Lighting, 2nd Ed. | publisher = The Electrical Engineer | date = 1894 | location = | pages = 145–197 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7YPbAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA193 | doi = | id = | isbn = }} The Tesla coil circuit is shown p. 193, fig. 127</ref><ref name="Tesla">The lecture is reprinted in {{cite book | last1 = Tesla | first1 = Nikola | title = The Nikola Tesla Treasury | publisher = Wilder Publications | date = 2007 | location = | pages = 68–107 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Nc0WvDfk2BMC&pg=PA103 | doi = | id = | isbn = 1934451894 }} The Tesla coil illustration is shown p. 103, fig. 32</ref><ref name="Sarkar1">{{cite book |last1 = Sarkar |first1 = T. K. |last2 = Mailloux |first2 = Robert |last3 = Oliner |first3 = Arthur A. et al |title = History of Wireless |publisher = John Wiley and Sons |date = 2006 |location = |pages = 268–270 |language = |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=NBLEAA6QKYkC&pg=PA270 |doi = |id = |isbn = 0471783013 }}, [http://www.ee-techs.com/techbook/wireless-3.pdf archive] {{webarchive|url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160517072919/http://www.ee-techs.com/techbook/wireless-3.pdf |date=2016-05-17 }}</ref> Although Tesla patented many similar circuits during this period, this was the first that contained all the elements of the Tesla coil: high voltage primary transformer, capacitor, spark gap, and air core "oscillation transformer".
{{breakafterimages}}
==Invention== {{multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | header = | image2 = System of electric lighting - Nikola Tesla US patent 454622 fig1.png | caption2 = First drawing of Tesla coil circuit from Tesla's April 25, 1891 patent.<ref name="US_Patent_454622" /> | width2 = 160 | image3 = Early Tesla coil drawing 1891.png | caption3 = Drawing of Tesla coil circuit from Tesla's May 20, 1891 lecture at [[Columbia University|Columbia College]], New York.<ref name="Martin1" /> | width3 = 160 | image4 = Elihu Thomson's Tesla coil circuit Feb 1892 rotated.png | caption4 = Elihu Thomson's Tesla coil, published February 1892, identical to Tesla's except for a compressed air spark blowout ''(J)''.<ref name="Thomson1892" /> | width4 = 160 | footer = }}
During the [[Industrial Revolution]] the electrical industry exploited [[direct current]] (DC) and low [[frequency]] [[alternating current]] (AC), but not much was known about frequencies above 20&nbsp;kHz, what are now called [[radio frequency|radio frequencies]]. In 1887, four years previously, [[Heinrich Hertz]] had discovered [[Hertzian wave]]s ([[radio wave]]s), electromagnetic waves which oscillated at very high frequencies.<ref name="Aitken">{{cite book | last1 = Aitken | first1 = Hugh G.J. | title = Syntony and Spark: The Origins of Radio | publisher = Princeton Univ. Press | date = 2014 | location = | pages = 23–25, 31–36 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Mez_AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA23 | doi = | id = | isbn = 1400857880 }}</ref><ref name="Carlson">{{cite book | last1 = Carlson | first1 = W. Bernard | title = Tesla: Inventor of the Electrical Age | publisher = Princeton University Press | date = 2013 | location = | pages = 119–125 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5I5c9j8BEn4C&pg=PA119 | doi = | id = | isbn = 1400846552 }}</ref><ref name="Uth">{{cite book | last1 = Uth | first1 = Robert | title = Tesla, Master of Lightning | publisher = Barnes and Noble Publishing | date = 1999 | location = | pages = 65–70 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=3W6_h6XG6VAC&pg=PA66&dq=tesla | doi = | id = | isbn = 0760710058 }}</ref> This attracted much attention, and a number of researchers began experimenting with high frequency currents.
Tesla's background was in the new field of [[alternating current]] power systems, so he understood transformers and resonance.<ref name="Carlson" /><ref name="Sarkar1" /> In 1888 he decided that high frequencies were the most promising field for research, and set up a laboratory at 33 South Fifth Avenue, New York for researching them, initially repeating Hertz's experiments.
He first developed [[alternator]]s as sources of high frequency current, but by 1890 found they were limited to frequencies of about 20&nbsp;kHz.<ref name="Sarkar1" /> In search of higher frequencies he turned to spark-excited resonant circuits.<ref name="Carlson" /> Tesla's innovation was in applying resonance to transformers.<ref name="Wheeler">"''Tesla is entitled to either distinct priority or independent discovery of''" three concepts in wireless theory: "''(1) the idea of inductive coupling between the driving and the working circuits (2) the importance of tuning both circuits, i.e. the idea of an 'oscillation transformer' (3) the idea of a capacitance loaded open secondary circuit''" {{cite journal | last = Wheeler | first = L. P. | title = Tesla's contribution to high frequency | journal = Electrical Engineering | volume = 62 | issue = 8 | pages = 355–357 | publisher = IEEE | date = August 1943 | issn = 0095-9197 | doi = 10.1109/EE.1943.6435874 }}</ref> [[Transformer]]s functioned differently at high frequencies than at the low frequencies used in power systems; the [[magnetic core|iron core]] in low frequency transformers caused energy losses due to [[eddy current]]s and [[hysteresis]].<ref name="Carlson" /> Tesla<ref name="Tesla1899">{{cite journal | last1 = Tesla | first1 = Nikola | title = Some experiments in Tesla's laboratory with currents of high frequencies and pressures | journal = Electrical Review | volume = 34 | issue = 13 | pages = 193–197 | publisher = Electrical Review Publishing Co. | location = New York | date = March 29, 1899 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5EQ_AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA194 | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = November 30, 2015}} p. 196-197 and fig. 2: Tesla describes the steps in his invention of the high frequency transformer.</ref> <ref name="Wheeler" /><ref name="Sarkar1" /> and [[Elihu Thomson]]<ref name="Strong" /><ref name="Pierce" /><ref name="Fleming">{{cite book | last1 = Fleming | first1 = John Ambrose | title = The Principles of Electric Wave Telegraphy and Telephony, 2nd Ed. | publisher = Longmans, Green and Co. | date = 1910 | location = London | pages = 581–582 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=qQFVAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA581&dq=tesla | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref> independently developed a new type of transformer without an iron core, the "[[oscillation transformer]]", and the Tesla coil circuit to drive it to produce high voltages.
Tesla invented the Tesla coil during efforts to develop a "wireless" lighting system, with [[gas discharge lamp|gas discharge light bulb]]s that would glow in an oscillating electric field from a high voltage, high frequency power source.<ref name="Carlson" /><ref name="Sarkar1" /> For a high frequency source Tesla powered a [[Ruhmkorff coil]] ([[induction coil]]) with his high frequency [[alternator]]. He found that the [[core loss]]es due to the high frequency current overheated the iron core in the Ruhmkorff coil and melted the insulation between the primary and secondary windings. To fix this problem Tesla changed the design so that there was an air gap instead of insulating material between the windings, and made the iron core adjustable so it could be moved in or out of the coil<ref>W. Bernard Carlson, Tesla: Inventor of the Electrical Age, Princeton University Press - 2013, page 122</ref> He eventually found the highest voltages could be produced when the iron core was omitted. Tesla also found he needed to put the [[capacitor]] normally used in the Ruhmkorff circuit between his alternator and the coil's primary winding to avoid burning out the coil. By adjusting the coil and capacitor Tesla found he could take advantage of the [[resonance]] set up between the two to achieve even higher frequencies.<ref>W. Bernard Carlson, Tesla: Inventor of the Electrical Age, Princeton University Press - 2013, page 124</ref> He found that the highest voltages were generated when the "closed" primary circuit with the capacitor was in [[resonance]] with the "open" secondary winding.<ref name="Wheeler" /><ref name="Sarkar1" /> {{breakafterimages}}
<gallery mode=packed heights="165px" style="text-align:center" > File:Tesla lab coil1.jpg|One of Tesla's early coils at his New York lab in 1892, with a conical secondary. File:Tesla prototype magnifying transmitter.jpg|Prototype "magnifying transmitter"<ref name="ElectricalRev11-1898">{{cite journal | title = Tesla's system of electric power transmission through natural media | journal = The Electrical Review| volume = 43 | issue = 1094 | pages = 709 | publisher = H. Alabaster, Gatehouse and Co. | location = New York | date = November 11, 1898 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=IelQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA709 | accessdate = August 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>Tesla stated in Nikola Tesla [http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Electrical-Experimenter/EE-1919-06.pdf My Inventions - Ch. 5: The Magnifying Transmitter], Electrical Experimenter, Vol. 7, No. 2, June 1919, p. 112, that this picture showed a prototype of his magnifying transmitter, a smaller version of the apparatus installed in his Colorado Springs lab.</ref> in Tesla's New York lab around 1898 producing 2.5 million volts. The round "spiderweb" secondary coil is visible in background File:Tesla electrical oscillator.gif|Compact coil designed by Tesla for use as an [[ozone]] generator for water treatment<ref name="TeslaJuly1919">{{cite journal | last1 = Tesla | first1 = Nikola | title = Electrical Oscillators | journal = Electrical Experimenter | volume = 7 | issue = 3 | pages = 228–229, 259–260 | publisher = Experimenter Publishing Co. | location = New York | date = July 1919 | url = http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Electrical-Experimenter/EE-1919-07.pdf | accessdate = August 20, 2015}}</ref> </gallery>
Tesla was not the first to invent this circuit.<ref name="Britannica1903">{{cite encyclopedia | title = Transformer | encyclopedia = Encyclopaedia Britannica, 10th Ed. | volume = 33 | pages = 426 | publisher = The Encyclopaedia Britannica Co. | date = 1903 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=cNdEAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA426&dq=tesla+%22oscillation+transformer%22#v=onepage&q=tesla%20%22oscillation%20transformer%22 | id = | accessdate = May 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Fleming" /> [[Henry Augustus Rowland|Henry Rowland]] built a spark-excited resonant transformer circuit ''(above)'' in 1889<ref name="Strong">{{cite book | last1 = Strong | first1 = Frederick Finch | title = High Frequency Currents | publisher = Rebman Co. | date = 1908 | location = New York | pages = 41–42 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=2S05vCsoKbkC&pg=PA41&dq=tesla+Oudin+d%27arsonval+%22elihu+thomson%22+Rowland | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref> and [[Elihu Thomson]] had experimented with similar circuits in 1890, including one which could produce 64 inch (1.6 m) sparks,<ref name="Thomson1892">{{cite journal | last1 = Thomson | first1 = Elihu | title = Induction by high potential discharges | journal = Electrical World | volume = 19 | issue = 8 | pages = 116–117 | publisher = W. J. Johnson Co. | location = New York | date = February 20, 1892 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=JUtEAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA117&dq=thomson | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = November 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name="ThomsonApril1893">{{cite journal|last1=Thomson|first1=Elihu|date=April 1893|title=High Frequency Electric Induction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ihBAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA52|journal=Technology Quarterly and Proceedings of Society of Arts|location=Boston|publisher=Massachusetts Inst. of Technology|volume=6|issue=1|pages=50–59|doi=|issn=|id=|accessdate=November 22, 2015|via=}}</ref><ref name="Thomson1906">{{cite web | last = Thomson | first = Elihu | title = Letter to Frederick Finch Strong | work = The Electrotherapy Museum website | publisher = Jeff Behary, Bellingham, Washington, USA. Reproduced by permission of The American Philosophical Society. | date = July 23, 1906 | url = http://www.electrotherapymuseum.com/2008/APS/StrongLetter.htm | doi = | accessdate = August 20, 2015}} In this letter Thomson lists papers he published in technical journals which support his claim to priority in inventing the "Tesla coil" resonant transformer circuit</ref> <ref name="Thomson">{{cite journal | last1 = Thomson | first1 = Elihu | title = Apparatus for obtaining high frequencies and pressures | journal = The Electrician | volume = 44 | issue = 2 | pages = 40–41 | publisher = The Electrician Publishing Co. | location = London | date = November 3, 1899 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5g1RAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA40&dq=tesla+elihu+thomson#v=onepage&q=tesla%20elihu%20thomson | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = May 1, 2015}}</ref> and other sources confirm Tesla was not the first.<ref name="Pierce">{{cite book | last1 = Pierce | first1 = George Washington | title = Principles of Wireless Telegraphy | publisher = McGraw-Hill Book Co. | date = 1910 | location = New York | pages = 93–95 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=v94OAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA94&dq=tesla+elihu+thomson | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref><ref name="Fessenden">{{cite journal | last1 = Fessenden | first1 = Reginald A. | title = Wireless Telephony | journal = Telephony | volume = 16 | issue = 2 | pages = 75 | publisher = The Telephony Publishing Co. | location = Chicago, Illinois | date = August 1908 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=vcE6AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA75&dq=tesla+elihu+thomson | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = May 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Fleming" /> However he was the first to see practical applications for it and patent it. Tesla did not perform detailed mathematical analyses of the circuit, relying instead on trial and error and his intuitive understanding of resonance.<ref name="Sarkar1" /> He even realized that the secondary coil functioned as a quarter-wave [[resonator]]; he specified the length of the wire in the secondary coil must be a quarter [[wavelength]] at the resonant frequency.<ref name="QuarterWave">"''The length of the...coil in each transformer should be approximately one quarter of the wave length of the electric disturbance in the circuit, this estimate being based on the velocity of propagation of the disturbaiice through the coil itself...''" US Patent No. 645576, Nikola Tesla, ''[http://www.google.com/patents/US645576 System of transmission of electrical energy]'', filed September 2, 1897; granted March 20, 1900</ref><ref name="Sarkar1" /> The first mathematical analyses of the circuit were done by [[Anton Oberbeck]] (1895)<ref name="Oberbeck">{{cite journal | last1 = Oberbeck | first1 = A. | title = Ueber den Verlauf der electrischen Schwingungen bei den Tesla'schen Versuchen (On the electrical oscillations in Tesla's experiments) | journal = Annalen der Physik | volume = 291 | issue = 8 | pages = 623–632 | publisher = Wiedemann | location = Berlin | date = 1895 | url = http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/andp.18952910808/abstract | issn = | doi = 10.1002/andp.18952910808 | id = | accessdate = May 1, 2015| bibcode = 1895AnP...291..623O }}</ref><ref name="Fleming" /> and [[Paul Drude]] (1904).<ref name="Drude">{{cite journal | last1 = Drude | first1 = P. | title = Über induktive Erregung zweier elektrischer Schwingungskreise mit Anwendung auf Periodenund Dämpfungsmessung, Teslatransformatoren und drahtlose Telegraphie (Of inductive excitation of two electric resonant circuits with application to measure-ment of oscillation periods and damping, Tesla coils, and wireless telegraphy) | journal = Annalen der Physik | volume = 13 | issue = 3 | pages = 512–561 | publisher = Wiley-VCH | location = | date = February 1904 | url = http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/andp.18943180306/abstract | issn = 1521-3889 | doi = 10.1002/andp.18943180306 | id = | accessdate = July 25, 2015| bibcode = 1904AnP...318..512D }}, [https://arxiv.org/pdf/1303.1588.pdf English translation]</ref><ref name="Denicolai1" />
{{breakafterimages}}
==Tesla's demonstrations== [[File:TeslaWirelessPower1891.png|thumb|upright=1.4|Tesla demonstrating wireless lighting at his 1891 lecture at [[Columbia College, Columbia University|Columbia College]].<ref name="Carlson2" /><ref name="Barrett">A description of a similar demonstration which Tesla organized at the Westinghouse exhibit at the 1893 Columbian Exposition in St. Louis is found in {{cite book |title=Electricity at the Columbian Exposition; Including an Account of the Exhibits in the Electricity Building, the Power Plant in Machinery Hall |last=Barrett |first=John Patrick |year=1894 |isbn= |pages=168–169 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=CLtIAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA169 |accessdate=29 November 2010}}</ref> The two metal sheets are connected to a Tesla coil oscillator, which applies a high [[radio frequency]] oscillating voltage. The oscillating electric field between the sheets [[ionize]]s the low pressure gas in the two long [[Geissler tube]]s he is holding, causing them to glow by [[fluorescence]], similar to [[neon light]]s, without wires. ]]
A charismatic showman and self-promoter, in 1891-1893 Tesla used the Tesla coil in dramatic public lectures demonstrating the new science of high voltage, high frequency electricity.<ref name="Carlson2">{{cite book | last1 = Carlson | first1 = W. Bernard | title = Tesla: Inventor of the Electrical Age | publisher = Princeton University Press | date = 2013 | location = | pages = 133–138 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5I5c9j8BEn4C&pg=PA133 | doi = | id = | isbn = 1400846552 }}</ref> The [[radio frequency]] AC electric currents produced by a Tesla coil did not behave like the DC or low frequency AC current scientists of the time were familiar with. In lectures at [[Columbia University|Columbia College]] May 20, 1891,<ref name="Martin1" /> scientific societies in Britain and France during an 1892 European speaking tour,<ref name="Martin2">Thomas Cummerford Martin 1894 ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=7YPbAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA198 The Inventions, Researches and Writings of Nikola Tesla, 2nd Ed.]'', p. 198-293</ref> the [[Franklin Institute]], Philadelphia in February 1893, and the [[National Electric Light Association]], St. Louis in March 1893,<ref name="Martin3">"''On light and other high frequency phenomena''", Thomas Cummerford Martin 1894 ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=7YPbAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA294 The Inventions, Researches and Writings of Nikola Tesla, 2nd Ed.]'', p. 294-373</ref> he impressed audiences with spectacular [[brush discharge]]s and [[streamer discharge|streamers]], heated iron by [[induction heating]], showed RF current could pass through insulators and be conducted by a single wire without a return path, and powered light bulbs and motors without wires.<ref name="Carlson2" /> He demonstrated that high frequency currents often did not cause the sensation of [[electric shock]], applying hundreds of thousands of volts to his own body,<ref name="Goldman" /><ref name="Carlson2" /> causing his body to light up with a glowing [[corona discharge]] in the darkened room. These lectures introduced the "Tesla oscillator" to the scientific community, and made Tesla internationally famous.<ref name="Sterling" /><ref name="Uth" /> {{breakafterimages}}
==Wireless power experiments== {{main|World Wireless System}} {{multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal | header = | image1 = TeslaWirelessIllustration.png | caption1 = Light bulb ''(bottom)'' powered wirelessly by "receiver" coil tuned to resonance with the huge "magnifying transmitter" coil at Tesla's Colorado Springs lab, 1899.<ref name="LongestTransmission" /> | width1 = 120 | image2 = US Patent 645576 Nikola Tesla 1897 System of transmission of electrical energy.png | caption2 = Tesla's proposed wireless power system, from his 1897 patent.<ref name="Patent645576" /> The transmitter ''(left)'' consists of a Tesla coil ''(A,C)'' driving an elevated capacitive terminal ''(B)'' suspended by a balloon ''(D)''. The receiver ''(right)'' is a similar terminal and resonant transformer. | width2 = 175 | footer = }}
Tesla employed the Tesla coil in his efforts to achieve [[wireless power|wireless power transmission]],<ref name="Lee" /> his lifelong dream. In the period 1891 to 1900 he used it to perform some of the first experiments in wireless power,<ref name="Curty" /><ref name="Shinohara">{{cite book | last1 = Shinohara | first1 = Naoki | title = Wireless Power Transfer via Radiowaves | publisher = John Wiley & Sons | date = 2014 | pages = 11 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=TwegAgAAQBAJ&pg=PP11 | isbn = 1118862961 }}</ref><ref name="LeeZhongHui">{{cite conference | first1 = C.K. | last1 = Lee | first2 = W.X. | last2 = Zhong | first3 = S.Y.R. | last3 = Hui | title = Recent Progress in Mid-Range Wireless Power Transfer | conference = The 4th Annual IEEE Energy Conversion Congress and Exposition (ECCE 2012) | pages = 3819–3821 | publisher = Inst. of Electrical and Electronic Engineers | date = September 5, 2012 | location = Raleigh, North Carolina | url = http://hub.hku.hk/bitstream/10722/189863/1/Content.pdf?accept=1 | accessdate = November 4, 2014}}</ref> transmitting radio frequency power across short distances by [[inductive coupling]] between coils of wire.<ref name="Shinohara" /><ref name="LeeZhongHui" /><ref name="Tesla1891" >Tesla, Nikola (May 20, 1891) [http://www.tfcbooks.com/tesla/1891-05-20.htm ''Experiments with Alternate Currents of Very High Frequency and Their Application to Methods of Artificial Illumination''], lecture before the American Inst. of Electrical Engineers, Columbia College, New York. Reprinted as a {{cite book | title = book of the same name by | publisher = Wildside Press | date = 2006 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=94eH3rULPy4C | isbn = 0809501627 }}</ref> In his early 1890s demonstrations such as those before the American Institute of Electrical Engineers<ref name="Tesla1891" /> and at the 1893 Columbian Exposition in Chicago he lit light bulbs from across a room.<ref name="LeeZhongHui" /> He found he could increase the distance by using a receiving [[LC circuit]] tuned to [[resonance]] with the Tesla coil's LC circuit,<ref name="Wheeler" /> transferring energy by [[resonant inductive coupling]].<ref name="LeeZhongHui" /> At his Colorado Springs laboratory during 1899-1900, by using voltages of the order of 10 million volts generated by his enormous [[magnifying transmitter]] coil (described below), he was able to light three incandescent lamps at a distance of about {{convert|100|feet|m}}.<ref name="LongestTransmission">The longest Tesla wireless power transmission for which there is credible evidence is probably his 1899 picture of a receiving coil with a 10 watt light bulb lit by power transmitted from his 300,000 watt magnifying transmitter. Tesla did not give the distance, but Marincic has claimed Tesla's lab notes indicate it was at a distance of 1,938 feet (591 m) from the transmitter. {{cite book|last1=Tesla|first1=Nikola|last2=Marincic|first2=Aleksandar|last3=Popovic|first3=Vojin|last4=Ciric|first4=Milan|title=From Colorado Springs to Long Island : research notes : Colorado Springs 1899-1900, New York 1900-1901|date=2008|publisher=Nikola Tesla Museum|location=Belgrade|isbn=9788681243442|page=169|url=https://teslauniverse.com/nikola-tesla/books/nikola-tesla-colorado-long-island-research-notes-colorado-springs-1899-1900-new}} This represents a transmission efficiency of only 0.0033%.</ref><ref name="Cheney">{{cite book |last=Cheney|first=Margaret |title=Tesla: Man Out of Time |publisher=Simon and Schuster |date=2011 |page=87 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HIuK7iLO9zgC&pg=PA87 |isbn=1-4516-7486-4}}</ref><ref name="CenturyMagazineCaption">Tesla was notoriously secretive about the distance he could transmit power. One of his few disclosures of details was in the caption of fig. 7 of his noted magazine article: ''[http://www.tfcbooks.com/tesla/1900-06-00.htm The Problem of Increasing Human Energy]'', Century magazine, June 1900. The caption reads: "''EXPERIMENT TO ILLUSTRATE AN INDUCTIVE EFFECT OF AN ELECTRICAL OSCILLATOR OF GREAT POWER - The photograph shows three ordinary incandescent lamps lighted to full candle-power by currents induced in a local loop consisting of a single wire forming a square of fifty feet each side, which includes the lamps, and which is at a distance of one hundred feet from the primary circuit energized by the oscillator. The loop likewise includes an electrical condenser, and is exactly attuned to the vibrations of the oscillator, which is worked at less than five percent of its total capacity.''"</ref> Today the resonant inductive coupling discovered by Tesla is a familiar concept in electronics, widely used in [[transformer|IF transformers]] and short range wireless power transmission systems<ref name="LeeZhongHui" /><ref name="Leyh">{{cite conference |first1 = G. E. |last1 = Leyh |first2 = M. D. |last2 = Kennan |title = Efficient wireless transmission of power using resonators with coupled electric fields |conference = NAPS 2008 40th North American Power Symposium, Calgary, September 28–30, 2008 |pages = 1–4 |publisher = Inst. of Electrical and Electronic Engineers |date = September 28, 2008 |url = http://lod.org/misc/Leyh/Papers/NAPS2008Final.pdf |doi = 10.1109/NAPS.2008.5307364 |isbn = 978-1-4244-4283-6 |accessdate = November 20, 2014 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304130428/http://lod.org/misc/Leyh/Papers/NAPS2008Final.pdf |archivedate = March 4, 2016 |df = }}</ref> such as cellphone charging pads.
It is now understood that [[inductive coupling|inductive]] and [[capacitive coupling]] are "[[Near and far field|near-field]]" effects,<ref name="LeeZhongHui" /> so they cannot be used for long-distance transmission.<ref name="LongestTransmission" /><ref name="Sazonov">{{cite book | last1 = Sazonov | first1 = Edward | last2 = Neuman | first2 = Michael R | title = Wearable Sensors: Fundamentals, Implementation and Applications | publisher = Elsevier | date = 2014 | pages = 253–255 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wGJzAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA253#v=onepage&q&f=false | isbn = 0124186661}}</ref><ref name="Agbinya2">{{cite journal | last1 = Agbinya | first1 = Johnson I. | title = Investigation of near field inductive communication system models, channels, and experiments | journal = Progress In Electromagnetics Research B | volume = 49 | pages = 130 | publisher = EMW Publishing | date = February 2013 | url = http://www.jpier.org/PIERB/pierb49/06.12120512.pdf | accessdate = January 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Bolic">{{cite book | last1 = Bolic | first1 = Miodrag | last2 = Simplot-Ryl | first2 = David | last3 = Stojmenovic | first3 = Ivan | title = RFID Systems: Research Trends and Challenges | publisher = John Wiley & Sons | date = 2010 | pages = 29 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=VansInOpixEC&pg=PA29 | isbn = 0470975660 }}</ref> However, Tesla was obsessed with developing a long range wireless power transmission system which could transmit power from power plants directly into homes and factories without wires, described in a visionary June 1900 article in ''[[Century Magazine]]''; "The Problem of Increasing Human Energy".<ref name="Tesla1900">{{cite journal | last = Tesla | first = Nikola | title = The Problem of Increasing Human Energy | journal = Century Magazine | publisher = The Century Co. | location = New York | date = June 1900 | url = http://www.tfcbooks.com/tesla/1900-06-00.htm | accessdate = November 20, 2014}}</ref> He claimed to be able to transmit power on a ''worldwide'' scale, using a method that involved conduction through the Earth and atmosphere.<ref name="Patent645576">US Patent No. 645576, Nikola Tesla, ''[http://www.google.com/patents/US645576 System of transmission of electrical energy]'', filed September 2, 1897; granted March 20, 1900</ref><ref name="Tesla1904">{{cite journal | last = Tesla | first = Nikola | title = The Transmission of Electric Energy Without Wires | journal = Electrical World and Engineer | volume = 43 | pages = 23760–23761 | publisher = McGraw Publishing Co. | date = March 5, 1904 | url = http://www.tfcbooks.com/tesla/1904-03-05.htm | accessdate = November 19, 2014}}, reprinted in ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=qPI5AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA30 Scientific American Supplement, Munn and Co., Vol. 57, No. 1483, June 4, 1904, p. 23760-23761]</ref><ref name="Broad">{{Cite news | last = Broad | first = William J. | title = A Battle to Preserve a Visionary’s Bold Failure | newspaper = New York Times | location = New York | pages = D1 | publisher = The New York Times Co. | date = May 4, 2009 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/05/science/05tesla.html | accessdate = November 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Lee">{{cite book | last1 = Lee | first1 = Thomas H. | title = The Design of CMOS Radio-Frequency Integrated Circuits | publisher = Cambridge Univ. Press | date = 2004 | location = | pages = 37–39 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=WqdzSq56lSQC&pg=PA38&dq=%22Tesla%22 | isbn = 0521835399 }}</ref><ref name="Carlson3" >[https://books.google.com/books?id=5I5c9j8BEn4C&pg=PA209 Carlson 2013 ''Tesla: Inventor of the Electrical Age, p. 209-210]</ref> Tesla believed that the entire Earth could act as an electrical resonator, and that by driving current pulses into the Earth at its [[resonant frequency]] from a grounded Tesla coil with an elevated capacitance, the potential of the Earth could be made to oscillate, creating global [[standing waves]], and this alternating current could be received with a capacitive antenna tuned to resonance with it at any point on Earth.<ref name="Cheney1" /><ref name="Sewall">{{cite book | last1 = Sewall | first1 = Charles Henry | title = Wireless telegraphy: its origins, development, inventions, and apparatus | publisher = D. Van Nostrand Co. | date = 1903 | location = | pages = 38–42 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=q_J3qYI5erkC&pg=PA38&dq=Tesla | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref><ref name="Tesla1907">{{cite journal | last1 = Tesla | first1 = Nikola | title = Tuned Lightning | journal = English Mechanic and World of Science | volume = | issue = | pages = | publisher = | location = | date = March 8, 1907 | url = http://www.tfcbooks.com/tesla/1907-03-08.htm | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = October 18, 2015}}, reprinted in {{cite book | last1 = Tesla | first1 = Nikola | title = The Nikola Tesla Treasury | publisher = Start Publications LLC | date = 2012 | location = | pages = 526 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=PmrsAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT526 | doi = | id = | isbn = 1627932569 }}</ref><ref name="Tesla1904" /> Another of his ideas was that transmitting and receiving terminals could be suspended in the air by balloons at {{convert|30,000|feet}} altitude, where the air pressure is lower.<ref name="Sewall" /><ref name="ElectricalRev11-1898" /><ref name="Patent645576" /><ref name="Lee" /> At this altitude, he thought, a layer of electrically conductive rarefied air would allow electricity to be sent at high voltages (hundreds of millions of volts) over long distances. Tesla envisioned building a global network of wireless power stations, which he called his "[[World Wireless System]]", which would transmit both information and electric power to everyone on Earth.<ref name="Carlson7" >[https://books.google.com/books?id=5I5c9j8BEn4C&pg=PA337 Carlson 2013 ''Tesla: Inventor of the Electrical Age, p. 337-346]</ref> There is no reliable evidence that he ever transmitted significant amounts of power beyond the short range demonstrations above.<ref name="LongestTransmission" /><ref name="Cheney3" /><ref name="Shinohara" /><ref name="Coe" /><ref name="Carlson" /><ref name="Tomar" /><ref name="Cooper" /><ref name="Brown" /><ref name="ColoradoSpringsPBS" /> {{breakafterimages}}
==Magnifying transmitter== {{see also| Colorado Springs Notes, 1899–1900}} {{multiple image | align = center | direction = horizontal | header = | image2 = Nikola Tesla, with his equipment EDIT.jpg | caption2 = Famous image of magnifying transmitter in operation with Tesla sitting next to it. This is a "trick" photo, a double exposure; Tesla was not in the room when the coil was operating.<ref name="Carlson9" /> | width2 = 183 | image3 = Tesla Colorado Springs lab-12 million volts.jpg | caption3 = Coil in operation, at -12 million volts. The 10 ft diameter "extra" coil is shown. The 51 ft diameter secondary coil is visible dimly in background, and in the previous photo. | width3 = 189 | image4 = Tesla Colorado Springs lab-magnifying transmitter with metal ball.jpg | caption4 = Discharge of same coil with a metal sphere capacitive terminal | width4 = 105 | image5 = Tesla Colorado Springs lab-primary circuit of Magnifying Transmitter.jpg | caption5 = Primary circuit, showing oil capacitor bank ''(boxes, foreground)'', 40&nbsp;kV supply transformer and rotary spark gap ''(rear)'', and part of secondary winding ''(wall, left)'' | width5 = 190 | footer = The huge "magnifying transmitter" coil at Tesla's Colorado Springs laboratory, 1899–1900, photos by photographer Dickenson Alley December 1899. The long arcs shown above were not a feature of the normal operation of the transmitter because they wasted energy; for these photos Tesla forced the machine to produce arcs by switching the power rapidly on and off.<ref name="Carlson9" /> }} [[Image:Tesla magnifying transmitter circuit.svg|thumb|upright=1.2|Circuit of magnifying transmitter at Tesla's Colorado Springs laboratory.<ref name="Denicolai2">[http://www.saunalahti.fi/dncmrc1/lthesis.pdf Denicolai, 2001, ''Tesla Transformer for Experimentation and Research'', Ch.2, p. 8-10]</ref><ref name="Sarkar2">[https://books.google.com/books?id=NBLEAA6QKYkC&pg=PA279 Sarkar et al. (2006) ''History of Wireless'', p. 279-280], [http://www.ee-techs.com/techbook/wireless-3.pdf archive] {{webarchive|url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160517072919/http://www.ee-techs.com/techbook/wireless-3.pdf |date=2016-05-17 }}</ref> ''C2'' represents the [[parasitic capacitance]] between the windings of coil ''L3''.]]
Tesla's wireless research required increasingly high voltages, and he had reached the limit of the voltages he could generate within the space of his New York lab. Between 1899 and 1900 he built a laboratory in [[Colorado Springs]] and performed experiments on wireless transmission there.<ref name="Sarkar2" /> He chose this location because the polyphase alternating current power distribution system had been introduced there and he had associates who were willing to give him all the power he needed without charging for it.<ref><u>Nikola Tesla On His Work With Alternating Currents and Their Application to Wireless Telegraphy, Telephony, and Transmission of Power</u>, Leland I. Anderson, 21st Century Books, 2002, p. 109, {{ISBN|1-893817-01-6}}.</ref> <!--primarily because of the frequent thunderstorms, the high altitude (where the air, being at a lower pressure, had a lower dielectric breakdown strength, making it easier to ionize), and the dryness of the air (minimizing leakage of electric charge through insulators).--> The Colorado Springs laboratory had one of the largest Tesla coils ever built, which Tesla called a "magnifying transmitter" as it was intended to transmit power to a distant receiver.<ref name="Tesla1919">{{cite journal | last1 = Tesla | first1 = Nikola | title = My Inventions V. - The Magnifying Transmitter | journal = Electrical Experimenter | volume = 7 | issue = 2 | pages = 112 | publisher = Experimenter Publishing Co. | location = New York | date = June 1919 | url = http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Electrical-Experimenter/EE-1919-06.pdf | issn = | doi = | id = | access-date = August 8, 2015}}, reprinted in Nikola Tesla, ''My Inventions'', The Philovox, 1919, Ch. 5 republished as {{cite book | last1 = Tesla | first1 = Nikola | title = My Inventions: The Autobiography of Nikola Tesla | publisher = Wilder Publications | date = 2007 | location = | pages = 53-16 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=E4r3BgAAQBAJ&pg=PT32&dq=%22swelling+to+enormous+proportions%22 | doi = | id = | isbn = 1934451770 }}</ref> With an input power of 300 kilowatts it could produce potentials of the order of 10 million volts,<ref name="Sarkar2"/><ref name="Cheney1">[https://books.google.com/books?id=HIuK7iLO9zgC&pg=PA188 Cheney, Margaret (2011) ''Tesla: Man Out of Time'', p.&nbsp;187–189]</ref> at frequencies of 50–150&nbsp;kHz, creating huge "lightning bolts" reportedly up to 135 feet long.<ref name="Sprott">{{cite book | last1 = Sprott | first1 = Julien C. | title = Physics Demonstrations: A Sourcebook for Teachers of Physics | publisher = Univ. of Wisconsin Press | date = 2006 | location = | pages = 192–195 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9wmgYl49YQ0C&pg=PA192&dq=%22tesla+coil%22 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0299215806 }}</ref><ref name="Coe" /> During experiments, it caused an overload which set fire to the alternator of the Colorado Springs power company, destroying it, and Tesla had to rebuild the alternator.<ref name="Sprott" />
In the magnifying transmitter, Tesla used a modified design (''see circuit'') which he had developed in his New York lab in the period 1895-1898,<ref name="My Inventions"><u>My Inventions: The Autobiography of Nikola Tesla</u>, Hart Brothers, 1982, Ch. 5, {{ISBN|0-910077-00-2}}</ref> and patented in 1902,<ref name="Patent1119732">US Patent No. 1119732, Nikola Tesla ''[https://www.google.com/patents/US1119732 Apparatus for transmitting electrical energy]'', filed January 18, 1902; granted December 1, 1914</ref><ref name="Gerekos3">[http://www.teslacoildesign.com/docs/TheTeslaCoil-Gerekos.pdf Gerekos, 2012, ''The Tesla Coil'', p. 19-20] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070623223754/http://www.teslacoildesign.com/docs/TheTeslaCoil-Gerekos.pdf |date=June 23, 2007 }}</ref> different from his previous double-tuned circuits. In addition to the primary (''L1'') and secondary (''L2'') coils, it had a third coil (''L3'') which he called the "extra" coil, not magnetically coupled to the others, attached to the top terminal of the secondary.<ref name="Sarkar2" /> When driven by the secondary it produced additional high voltage by [[resonance]], being adjusted to resonate with its own [[parasitic capacitance]] (''C2'')<ref name="Sarkar2" /> The use of a series-fed resonator coil to generate high voltages was independently discovered by [[Paul Marie Oudin]] in 1893 and employed in his [[Oudin coil]].<ref name="Martin" />
The Colorado Springs apparatus consisted of a 51-foot-diameter (15.5&nbsp;m) Tesla transformer composed of a secondary winding (''L2'') of 50 turns of heavy wire wound on a 6-foot-high (2&nbsp;m) circular wooden "fence" around the periphery of the lab, and a single-turn primary (''L1'') either mounted on the fence or buried in the ground under it.<ref name="Shunamen">{{cite journal | last1 = Shunamen | first1 = Fred | title = 12 Million Volts | journal = Radio-Electronics | volume = 47 | issue = 6 | pages = 32–34, 69 | publisher = Gernsback Publications, Inc. | location = | date = June 1976 | url = http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Radio-Electronics/70s/1976/Radio-Electronics-1976-06.pdf | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Carlson4" >[https://books.google.com/books?id=5I5c9j8BEn4C&pg=PA267 Carlson 2013 ''Tesla: Inventor of the Electrical Age'', p.&nbsp;267–268]</ref> The primary was connected to a bank of oil [[capacitor]]s (''C1'') to make a [[tuned circuit]], with a rotary spark gap ''(SG)'', powered by 20 to 40 kilovolts from a powerful utility step-up transformer (''T''). The top of the secondary was connected to the 100-turn 8&nbsp;ft (2.4&nbsp;m) diameter "extra" or "resonator" coil ''(L3)'' in the center of the room. Its high-voltage end was connected to a telescoping 143-foot (43.6&nbsp;m) "antenna" rod with a 30-inch (1&nbsp;m) metal ball on top which could project through the roof of the lab. By cranking the rod up or down he could adjust the capacitance in the circuit of the extra coil, tuning it to resonance with the rest of the circuit.<ref name="Carlson9" >[https://books.google.com/books?id=5I5c9j8BEn4C&pg=PA297 Carlson 2013 ''Tesla: Inventor of the Electrical Age, p.&nbsp;297–299]</ref>
{{breakafterimages}}
==Wardenclyffe tower== {{main|Wardenclyffe tower}} {{multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal | header = | image1 = Tesla Broadcast Tower 1904.jpeg | caption1 = [[Wardenclyffe Tower]] wireless station, essentially a huge Tesla coil intended as a prototype transatlantic [[radiotelegraphy]] and wireless power transmitter, built by Tesla at Shoreham, NY, 1901-1902. It was never completed. | width1 = 272 | image2 = US patent 1119732 Nikola Tesla 1907 Apparatus for transmitting electrical energy.png | caption2 = Design on which the Wardenclyffe plant was based, from Tesla's 1902 patent<ref name="Patent1119732" /> | width2 = 187 | footer = }}
In 1901, convinced his wireless theories were correct, Tesla with financing from banker [[J. P. Morgan]] began construction of a high-voltage wireless station, now called the [[Wardenclyffe Tower]], at [[Shoreham, New York]].<ref name="Tesla1904" /><ref name="Sarkar4">{{cite book |last1 = Sarkar |first1 = T. K. |last2 = Mailloux |first2 = Robert |last3 = Oliner |first3 = Arthur A. et al |title = History of Wireless |publisher = John Wiley and Sons |date = 2006 |location = |pages = 283 |language = |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=NBLEAA6QKYkC&pg=PA283 |doi = |id = |isbn = 0471783013 }}, [http://www.ee-techs.com/techbook/wireless-3.pdf archive] {{webarchive|url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160517072919/http://www.ee-techs.com/techbook/wireless-3.pdf |date=2016-05-17 }}</ref> Although it was built as a transatlantic [[radiotelegraphy]] station, Tesla also intended it to transmit electric power without wires as a prototype transmitter for his proposed "[[World Wireless System]]".<ref name="Tesla1919" /><ref name="Carlson7" /> Essentially an enormous Tesla coil, it consisted of a powerhouse with a 400-horsepower generator and a 187-foot (57&nbsp;m) tower topped by a 68-foot (21&nbsp;m) diameter metal dome capacitive electrode.<ref name="Tesla1919" /><ref name="Carlson6" >[https://books.google.com/books?id=5I5c9j8BEn4C&pg=PA318 Carlson 2013 ''Tesla: Inventor of the Electrical Age, p. 318-327]</ref> The circuit he used was a version of the "magnifying transmitter" he built at Colorado Springs ''(above)''. Underneath the surface was an elaborate [[ground (electricity)|ground]] system that Tesla said was needed to "grip the earth" to create the oscillating earth currents which he believed would transmit the power.
By 1904 his investors had pulled out<ref name="Carlson7" /> and the facility was never completed; it was torn down in 1916.<ref name="Broad" /><ref name="Tesla1919" /> Although Tesla seems to have believed his wireless power ideas were proven,<ref name="Coe" /> he had a history of making claims that he had not confirmed by experiment,<ref name="Hawkins">{{cite journal | last = Hawkins | first = Lawrence A. | title = Nikola Tesla: His Work and Unfulfilled Promises | journal = The Electrical Age | volume = 30 | issue = 2 | pages = 107–108 | date = February 1903 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=slc3AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA99 | accessdate = November 4, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Papadopoulos" /><ref name="Carlson5">{{cite book | last1 = Carlson | first1 = W. Bernard | title = Tesla: Inventor of the Electrical Age | publisher = Princeton University Press | date = 2013 | pages = 294, 300–301 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5I5c9j8BEn4C&pg=PA294 | isbn = 1400846552 }}</ref> and there seems to be no evidence that he ever transmitted significant power beyond the short-range demonstrations mentioned above.<ref name="LongestTransmission" /><ref name="Cheney3">{{cite book | last1 = Cheney | first1 = Margaret | last2 = Uth | first2 = Robert | last3 = Glenn | first3 = Jim | title = Tesla, Master of Lightning | publisher = Barnes & Noble Publishing | date = 1999 | pages = 90–92 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=3W6_h6XG6VAC&pg=PA92#v=onepage&q&f=false | isbn = 0760710058 }}</ref><ref name="Shinohara" /><ref name="Coe">{{cite book | last1 = Coe | first1 = Lewis | title = Wireless Radio: A History | publisher = McFarland | date = 2006 | pages = 111–113 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=W1JAeg1PiWIC&pg=PA112 | isbn = 0786426624 }}</ref><ref name="Carlson" /><ref name="Tomar">{{cite journal | last1 = Tomar | first1 = Anuradha | last2 = Gupta | first2 = Sunil | title = Wireless Power Transmission: Applications and Components | journal = International Journal of Engineering Research & Technology | volume = 1 | issue = 5 | date = July 2012 | url = https://www.academia.edu/5561926/Wireless_power_Transmission_Applications_and_Components | issn = 2278-0181 | accessdate = November 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Brown">{{cite journal | last1 = Brown | first1 = William C. | title = The history of power transmission by radio waves | journal = MTT-Trans. on Microwave Theory and Technique | volume = 32 | issue = 9 | pages = 1230–1234 | publisher = Inst. of Electrical and Electronic Engineers | date = 1984 | url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/3128972_The_History_of_Power_Transmission_by_Radio_Waves | accessdate = November 20, 2014 | doi=10.1109/tmtt.1984.1132833}}</ref><ref name="ColoradoSpringsPBS">{{cite web | title = Life and Legacy: Colorado Springs | work = Tesla: Master of Lightning - companion site for 2000 PBS television documentary | publisher = PBS.org, Public Broadcasting Service website | date = 2000 | url = https://www.pbs.org/tesla/ll/ll_colspr.html | accessdate = November 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Cooper">{{cite book | last1 = Cooper | first1 = Christopher | title = The Truth About Tesla: The Myth of the Lone Genius in the History of Innovation | publisher = Race Point Publishing | date = 2015 | location = | pages = 171–172 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=weo-CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA172 | doi = | id = | isbn = 1631060309 }}</ref> The few reports of long-distance power transmission by Tesla are not from reliable sources. For example, a widely repeated myth is that in 1899 he wirelessly lit 200 light bulbs at a distance of {{convert|26|miles|km}}.<ref name="Cheney3" /><ref name="Coe" /> There is no independent confirmation of this supposed demonstration;<ref name="Cheney3" /><ref name="Coe" /> Tesla did not mention it,<ref name="Coe" /> and it does not appear in his laboratory notes.<ref name="Cheney1" /><ref name="Marinčić">{{cite book | last1 = Tesla | first1 = Nikola | editor-last = Marinčić | editor-first = Aleksandar | title = Colorado Springs Notes, 1899-1900 | publisher = The Nikola Tesla Museum | date = 1977 | location = Beograd, Yugoslavia | url = http://www.bibliotecapleyades.net/tesla/coloradonotes/coloradonotes.htm }}</ref> It originated in 1944 from Tesla's first biographer, John J. O'Neill,<ref name="Cheney" /> who said he pieced it together from "fragmentary material... in a number of publications".<ref name="O'Neill">{{cite book | last1 = O'Neill | first1 = John J. | title = Prodigal Genius: The life of Nikola Tesla | publisher = Ives Washburn, Inc. | date = 1944 | pages = 193 | url = http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015013060820;view=1up;seq=207 }}</ref>
In the 100 years since, others such as Robert Golka<ref name="Shunamen" /><ref name="Golka" /><ref name="Lawren" /> have built equipment similar to Tesla's, but long-distance power transmission has not been demonstrated,<ref name="Leyh1">For example, using Tesla coils Leyh and Kennan only achieved 1.5% power throughput at a distance of 30 meters, only 5 times the transmitter diameter. {{cite conference |first1 = G. E. |last1 = Leyh |first2 = M. D. |last2 = Kennan |title = Efficient wireless transmission of power using resonators with coupled electric fields |conference = NAPS 2008 40th North American Power Symposium, Calgary, September 28–30, 2008 |pages = 1–4 |publisher = Inst. of Electrical and Electronic Engineers |date = September 28, 2008 |location = |url = http://lod.org/misc/Leyh/Papers/NAPS2008Final.pdf |doi = 10.1109/NAPS.2008.5307364 |id = |isbn = 978-1-4244-4283-6 |accessdate = November 20, 2014 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304130428/http://lod.org/misc/Leyh/Papers/NAPS2008Final.pdf |archivedate = March 4, 2016 |df = }}</ref><ref name="LeeZhongHui" /><ref name="Cheney" /><ref name="Coe" /> and the scientific consensus is his World Wireless system would not have worked.<ref name="Belohlavek1">{{cite book | last1 = Belohlavek | first1 = Peter | last2 = Wagner | first2 = John W | title = Innovation: The Lessons of Nikola Tesla | publisher = Blue Eagle Group | date = 2008 | pages = 78–79 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=8sLRSmrGbpsC&pg=PA78 | isbn = 9876510096 }}</ref><ref name="Curty">{{cite book | last1 = Curty | first1 = Jari-Pascal | last2 = Declercq | first2 = Michel | last3 = Dehollain | first3 = Catherine | last4 = Joehl | first4 = Norbert | title = Design and Optimization of Passive UHF RFID Systems | publisher = Springer | date = 2006 | pages = 4 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=uFjpH3Cl7z8C&pg=PA4#v=onepage&q&f=false | isbn = 0387447105 }}</ref><ref name="Shinohara" /><ref name="Broad" /><ref name="Coe" /><ref name="Tomar" /><ref name="Papadopoulos">{{cite web | title = Dennis Papadopoulos interview | work = Tesla: Master of Lightning - companion site for 2000 PBS television documentary | publisher = PBS.org, Public Broadcasting Service website | date = 2000 | url = https://www.pbs.org/tesla/dis/papad.html | access-date = November 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Cooper" /> Contemporary scientists point out that while Tesla's coils (with appropriate antennas) can function as radio transmitters, transmitting energy in the form of [[radio wave]]s, the frequency he used, around 150&nbsp;kHz, is far too low for practical long-range power transmission.<ref name="Shinohara" /><ref name="Coe" /><ref name="Brown" /> At these [[wavelength]]s the radio waves spread out in all directions and cannot be focused on a distant receiver.<ref name="Curty" /><ref name="Shinohara" /><ref name="Coe" /><ref name="Tomar" /><ref name="Papadopoulos" /> Tesla's world power transmission scheme remains today what it was in Tesla's time: a bold, fascinating dream.<ref name="Broad" /><ref name="Tomar" /> {{breakafterimages}}
==Use in radio== {{main|Spark-gap transmitter}} {{multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal | header = | image1 = Powerful spark gap transmitter.png | caption1 = Powerful spark-gap transmitter, showing series spark gaps ''(horizontal cylindrical objects)'', Leyden jar capacitors (''vertical cylinders, rear''), and resonant transformer (''top'') | width1 = 180 | image2 = Spark gap transmitter-Marconi patent 763772 fig 1.png | caption2 = Spark transmitter circuit from Marconi's 1900 patent.<ref name="Patent763772" /> Its similarity to a Tesla coil can be seen; the only difference is the addition of a variable inductor (''g'') to tune the antenna (''f'') to resonance.<ref name="Rockman" /><ref name="Sterling" /> | width2 = 148 | footer = }}
:"[The Tesla coil] ''was invented not for wireless but for making vacuum lamps glow without external electrodes, and it later played a principal part in other hands in the operation of big spark stations.''" --William H. Eccles, 1933<ref name="Eccles">{{cite book | last1 = Eccles | first1 = William H. | title = Wireless | publisher = T. Butterworth, Ltd. | date = 1933 | location = | pages = 80 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=1NtHAAAAIAAJ&q=eccles+tesla+%22vacuum+lamps+glow%22+%22big+spark+stations%22 | doi = | id = | isbn = }} quoted in [https://books.google.com/books?id=NBLEAA6QKYkC&pg=PA353 Sarkar, Mailloux, Oliner (2006) ''History of Wireless'', p. 268]. Eccles was a contemporary of Tesla.</ref>
One of the largest applications of the Tesla coil circuit was in early [[radio transmitter]]s called [[spark gap transmitter]]s. The first radio wave generators, invented by Heinrich Hertz in 1887, were spark gaps connected directly to [[Antenna (radio)|antennas]], powered by [[induction coil]]s.<ref name="Sarkar3">[https://books.google.com/books?id=NBLEAA6QKYkC&pg=PA353 Sarkar et al (2006) ''History of Wireless'', p. 352-353, 355-357], [http://www.ee-techs.com/techbook/wireless-3.pdf archive] {{webarchive|url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160517072919/http://www.ee-techs.com/techbook/wireless-3.pdf |date=2016-05-17 }}</ref><ref name="Aitken2">[https://books.google.com/books?id=Mez_AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA71&dq=tesla Aitken, Hugh 2014 ''Syntony and Spark: The origins of radio, p.&nbsp;70–73]</ref><ref name="Uth" /> Because they lacked a [[resonant circuit]], these [[transmitter]]s produced highly [[damped wave|damped]] radio waves. As a result, their transmissions occupied an extremely wide [[bandwidth (signal processing)|bandwidth]] of frequencies. When multiple transmitters were operating in the same area their frequencies overlapped and they interfered with one another, causing garbled reception. There was no way for a receiver to select one signal over another.<ref name="Aitken2" /><ref name="Sarkar3" />
In 1892 [[William Crookes]], a friend of Tesla, had given a lecture<ref name="Crookes">{{cite journal | last1 = Crookes | first1 = William | title = Some Possibilities of Electricity | journal = The Fortnightly Review | volume = 51 | issue = | pages = 174–176 | publisher = Chapman and Hall | location = London | date = February 1, 1892 | url = http://www.tfo.upm.es/ImperialismoWeb/ArtCrookes.htm | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = August 19, 2015}}</ref> on the uses of radio waves in which he suggested using [[resonance]] to reduce the bandwidth in transmitters and receivers. By using resonant circuits, different transmitters could be "tuned" to transmit on different frequencies. With narrower bandwidth, separate transmitter frequencies would no longer overlap, so a receiver could receive a particular transmission by "tuning" its resonant circuit to the same frequency as the transmitter.<ref name="Sarkar3" /><ref name="Uth" /><ref name="Rockman">{{cite book | last1 = Rockman | first1 = Howard B. | title = Intellectual Property Law for Engineers and Scientists | publisher = John Wiley and Sons | date = 2004 | location = | pages = 196–199 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=6B88P-32IIQC&pg=PA196 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0471697397 }}</ref> This is the system used in all modern radio.
With an appropriate wire antenna, the Tesla coil circuit could function as such a narrow-bandwidth radio transmitter.<ref name="Tilbury1">{{cite book |last=Tilbury |first=Mitch |title=The Ultimate Tesla Coil Design and Construction Guide |publisher=McGraw-Hill Professional |date=2007 |location=New York |page=1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o39HRjMqTuwC&pg=PT27&dq=%22tesla+coil%22+spark+transmitter#v=onepage&q=%22tesla%20coil%22%20spark%20transmitter&f=false |isbn=0-07-149737-4}}</ref><ref name="Pierce" /><ref name="Sprott" /><ref name="PBS">{{cite web |last=Uth |first=Robert |title=Tesla coil |date=December 12, 2000 |work=Tesla: Master of Lightning |publisher=PBS.org |url= https://www.pbs.org/tesla/ins/lab_tescoil.html|accessdate=2008-05-20}}</ref> In his March 1893 St. Louis lecture,<ref name="Martin3" /> Tesla demonstrated a wireless system that was the first use of [[tuned circuit]]s in radio, although he used it for wireless power transmission, not radio communication.<ref name="Sterling">{{cite book | last1 = Sterling | first1 = Christopher H. | title = Biographical Encyclopedia of American Radio | publisher = Routledge | date = 2013 | location = | pages = 382–383 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=mdQq-663faAC&pg=PA383&dq=tesla | doi = | id = | isbn = 1136993754 }}</ref><ref name="Uth" /><ref name="Aitken1">[https://books.google.com/books?id=Mez_AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA254&dq=tesla Aitken, Hugh 2014 ''Syntony and Spark: The origins of radio, p. 254-255, 259]</ref><ref name="Rockman" /><ref name="Klooster">{{cite book | last1 = Klooster | first1 = John W. | title = Icons of Invention | publisher = ABC-CLIO | date = 2007 | location = | pages = 160–161 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=WKuG-VIwID8C&pg=PA161&dq=Tesla | doi = | id = | isbn = 0313347433 }}</ref><ref name="Cheney4" /> A grounded spark-excited capacitor-tuned Tesla transformer attached to an elevated wire antenna transmitted radio waves, which were received across the room by a wire antenna attached to a receiver consisting of a second grounded resonant transformer tuned to the transmitter's frequency, which lighted a [[Geissler tube]].<ref name="Regal">{{cite book | last1 = Regal | first1 = Brian | title = Radio: The Life Story of a Technology | publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group | date = 2005 | location = | pages = 21–23 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=N2rNO6FX8o4C&pg=PA22&dq=Tesla | doi = | id = | isbn = 0313331677 }}</ref><ref name="Sarkar3" /><ref name="Rockman" /><ref name="Cheney4">[https://books.google.com/books?id=HIuK7iLO9zgC&pg=PA96 Cheney, Margaret (2011) ''Tesla: Man Out Of Time'', p.&nbsp;96–97]</ref> This system, patented by Tesla on September 2, 1897,<ref name="Patent645576" /> was the first use of the "four-circuit" concept later claimed by [[Guglielmo Marconi]].<ref name="FourCircuit">The "four circuit" radio system, which Marconi claimed in his 1900 patent, meant a transmitter and receiver which each contained a resonant transformer and thus were divided into primary and secondary circuits. All four circuits were tuned to the same frequency, one side by capacitors, and the other side by the capacitance of the antenna; "the use of two high frequency circuits in the transmitter and two in the receiver, all four so adjusted to be resonant at the same frequency or multiples of it."{{cite web | last = | first = | title = No. 369 (1943) Marconi Wireless Co. of America v. United States | work = United States Supreme Court decision | publisher = Findlaw.com website | date = June 21, 1943 | url = https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-supreme-court/320/1.html | doi = | access-date = March 14, 2017}} This was identical to the system Tesla demonstrated in 1893. The advantage of this system was that due to the resonant transformers both the receiver and transmitter had much narrower bandwidth than previous circuits.</ref><ref name="Cheney4" /><ref name="Sterling" /><ref name="Klooster" /> However, Tesla was mainly interested in wireless power and never developed a practical radio ''communication'' system.<ref name="Coe" /><ref name="Smith">{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Craig B. |title=Lightning: Fire from the Sky|publisher=Dockside Consultants Inc. |date=2008 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iGZw0qPDk8YC&pg=PT11&dq=%22tesla+coil%22+%22high+voltage%22+%22low+current%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=LREyUrZ65ZOIAu_GgMgL&ved=0CFsQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=%22tesla%20coil%22%20%22high%20voltage%22%20%22low%20current%22&f=false |isbn=0-615-24869-1}}</ref><ref name="Regal" /><ref name="Sarkar3" /> He never believed that radio waves could be used for practical communication, instead clinging to an erroneous theory that radio communication was due to currents in the Earth.<ref name="TrueWireless">{{cite journal | last1 = Tesla | first1 = Nikola | title = The True Wireless | journal = Electrical Experimenter | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | pages = 28–30, 61 | publisher = Experimenter Publishing Co. | location = New York | date = May 1919 | url = http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Electrical-Experimenter/EE-1919-05.pdf | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = February 20, 2017}} archived on [http://www.tfcbooks.com/tesla/1919-05-00.htm tfcbooks]</ref>
Practical [[radiotelegraphy]] communication systems were developed by Marconi beginning in 1895. By 1897 the advantages of narrow-bandwidth (lightly damped) systems noted by Crookes were recognized, and resonant circuits, [[capacitor]]s and [[inductor]]s, were incorporated in transmitters and receivers.<ref name="Aitken1" /> The "closed primary, open secondary" resonant transformer circuit used by Tesla proved a superior transmitter,<ref name="Klooster" /> because the loosely-coupled transformer partially isolated the oscillating primary circuit from the energy-radiating antenna circuit, reducing the damping, allowing it to produce long "ringing" waves which had a narrower bandwidth.<ref name="Fleming" /><ref name="Pierce" /><ref name="Sarkar3" /><ref name="Marconi">Marconi describes his discovery of this principle, and admits his circuit used the "Tesla coil", in {{cite journal | last1 = Marconi | first1 = Guglielmo | title = Syntonic Wireless Telegraphy | journal = The Electrician | volume = | issue = | pages = | publisher = The Electrician Publishing Co. | date = May 24, 1901 | url = http://teslacollection.com/tesla_articles/1901/the_electrician/guglielmo_marconi/syntonic_wireless_telegraphy | issn = | doi = | id = | access-date = April 8, 2017}}</ref> Versions of the circuit were patented by Marconi,<ref name="Patent763772" /><ref name="Klooster" /> [[John Stone Stone]]<ref name="Patent714756">US Patent no. 714,756, John Stone Stone [https://www.google.com/patents/US714756 Method of electric signaling], filed: February 8, 1900, granted: December 2, 1902</ref> and [[Oliver Lodge]],<ref name="Patent609154">US Patent no. 609,154 Oliver Joseph Lodge, [http://www.google.com/patents/US609154 Electric Telegraphy], filed: February 1, 1898, granted: August 16, 1898</ref> and were widely used in radio for twenty years.<ref name="Uth" /><ref name="Aitken1" /><ref name="Lee" /><ref name="Sarkar3" /><ref name="Rockman" /> In 1906 [[Max Wien]] invented the quenched or "series" spark gap, which extinguished the spark after the energy had been transferred to the secondary, allowing the secondary to oscillate freely after that, reducing damping and bandwidth still more.
Although their damping had been reduced as much as possible, spark transmitters still produced [[damped wave]]s which had a wide bandwidth, creating interference with other transmitters. Around 1920 they became obsolete, superseded by [[vacuum tube]] transmitters which generated [[continuous wave]]s at a single frequency, which could also be [[modulation|modulated]] to carry sound. Tesla's [[resonant transformer]] continued to be used in vacuum tube transmitters and receivers, and is a key component in radio to this day.<ref name="Belohlavek">"''Unfortunately, the common misunderstanding by most people today is that the Tesla coil is merely a device that produces a spectacular exhibit of sparks which tittilates audiences. Nevertheless, its circuitry is fundamental to all radio transmission''" {{cite book|last1=Belohlavek|first1=Peter|last2=Wagner|first2=John W|title=Innovation: The Lessons of Nikola Tesla|publisher=Blue Eagle Group|date=2008|page=110|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8sLRSmrGbpsC&pg=PA110|isbn=9876510096}}</ref>
During the "spark era" the radio engineering profession gave credit to Tesla;<ref name="Sarkar3" /> his circuit became known as the "Tesla coil" or "Tesla transformer".<ref name="Uth" /><ref name="Pierce" /><ref name="Mazzotto">{{cite book|last1=Mazzotto|first1=Domenico|title=Wireless telegraphy and telephony|publisher=Whittaker and Co.|date=1906|page=146|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CPZUAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA146#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> However Tesla did not benefit financially, due to competing patent claims. Marconi had claimed rights to the "closed primary open secondary" transmitter circuit in his controversial 1900 "four circuit" wireless patent.<ref name="Patent763772">US Patent no. 763,772, Guglielmo Marconi, [https://www.google.com/patents/US763772 Apparatus for wireless telegraphy], filed: November 10, 1900, granted: June 28, 1904. Corresponding British patent no. 7777, Guglielmo Marconi, [http://worldwide.espacenet.com/publicationDetails/biblio?CC=GB&NR=190007777&KC=&FT=E&locale=en_EP Improvements in apparatus for wireless telegraphy], filed: April 26, 1900, granted: April 13, 1901</ref><ref name="FourCircuit" /><ref name="Klooster" /><ref name="Lee" /><ref name="Rockman" /> Tesla sued Marconi in 1915 for patent infringement, but didn't have the resources to pursue the action.<ref name="Sarkar3" /><ref name="Klooster" /><ref name="Aitken1" /><ref name="Lee" /> However, in 1943, in a separate suit brought by the [[Marconi Company]] against the US government for use of its patents in World War I, the [[Supreme Court of the United States|US Supreme Court]] invalidated Marconi's 1900 patent claim to the "four circuit" concept.<ref name="Findlaw">{{cite web | last = | first = | title = No. 369 (1943) Marconi Wireless Co. of America v. United States | work = United States Supreme Court decision | publisher = Findlaw.com website | date = June 21, 1943 | url = https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-supreme-court/320/1.html | doi = | access-date = March 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name="Uth" /><ref name="Lee" /><ref name="Rockman" /><ref name="Sarkar">{{cite book|last1=Sarkar|first1=T. K.|last2=Mailloux|first2=Robert|last3=Oliner|first3=Arthur A.|display-authors=etal|title=History of Wireless|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|date=2006|pages=286, 84|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NBLEAA6QKYkC&pg=PA286&dq=tesla|isbn=0-471-78301-3}}, [http://www.ee-techs.com/techbook/wireless-3.pdf archive] {{webarchive|url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160517072919/http://www.ee-techs.com/techbook/wireless-3.pdf |date=2016-05-17 }}</ref> The ruling cited the prior patents of Tesla, Lodge, and Stone,<ref name="Sarkar3" /><ref name="Uth" /> but did not decide which of these parties had rights to the circuit.<ref name="Lee" /><ref name="Klooster" /><ref name="Rockman" /> By that time the issue was moot; the patent had expired in 1915 and spark transmitters had long been obsolete.
Although there is some disagreement over the role Tesla himself played in the invention of radio,<ref name="White">{{cite web | last = White | first = Thomas H. | authorlink = | title = Nikola Tesla: The Guy Who DIDN'T "Invent Radio" | work = United States Early Radio History | publisher = T. H. White's personal website | date = November 1, 2012 | url = https://earlyradiohistory.us/tesla.htm | doi = | accessdate = November 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name="Uth" /><ref name="Lee" /><ref name="Sarkar" /> sources agree on the importance of his circuit in early radio transmitters.<ref name="Rockman" /><ref name="Gerekos2">[http://www.teslacoildesign.com/docs/TheTeslaCoil-Gerekos.pdf Gerekos, 2012, ''The Tesla Coil'', p. 1]</ref><ref name="Sprott" /><ref name="PBS" /><ref name="Klooster" /><ref name="Sarkar3" /><ref name="Belohlavek" /> From a modern perspective, most spark transmitters could be regarded as Tesla coils.<ref name="Sprott" /><ref name="Tilbury1" /> {{breakafterimages}}
==Use in medicine== {{multiple image | align = center | direction = horizontal | header = | image1 = Ducretet Tesla coil.jpg | caption1 = Small Tesla coil for [[electrotherapy]], 1905. The Tesla transformer is immersed in a tank of oil for insulation to prevent arcs. | width1 = 199 | image2 = Treatment of knee with Oudin coil.jpg | caption2 = Effluvation treatment of knee with an [[Oudin coil]] ''(left)'', a high voltage transformer similar to a Tesla coil, 1915 | width2 = 129 | image3 = Tesla coil (Rankin Kennedy, Electrical Installations, Vol V, 1903).jpg | caption3 = Tesla electrotherapy coil manufactured by Adolphe Gaiffe, around 1900. The primary capacitor is in the box; the spark gap is mounted on top. | width3 = 225 | image4 = The treatment of cancer by cytolsis. Wellcome M0015160.jpg | caption4 = Treatment of cancer with an Oudin coil ''(left)'', 1910. The [[induction coil]] that powers the Oudin coil is behind the patient's head. | width4 = 207 | image5 = Hercules Tesla-Thomson electrotherapy unit 1907.jpg | caption5 = Combined Tesla / D'Arsonval / Oudin electrotherapy and x-ray outfit 1907 | width5 = 134 | footer = }} {{multiple image | align = center | direction = horizontal | header = | image1 = Diabetes electrotherapy with vacuum electrode 1922.jpg | caption1 = Electrotherapy treatment of [[diabetes]] with a vacuum electrode, 1922. The series spark gap is visible mounted on the front of the machine. | width1 = 200 | image2 = Spark diathermy machine 1921 parts labeled.jpg | caption2 = Longwave spark diathermy machine using Tesla circuit, 1921. | width2 = 208 | image3 = Diathermy of elbow 1945.jpg | caption3 = Diathermy of elbow 1945 | width3 = 165 | image4 = Violet ray wand glow Hochfrequenz 309.JPG | caption4 = Vacuum electrode "violet ray" wand in operation. | width4 = 101 | image5 = Violet wand.JPG | caption5 = A [[violet ray]] wand, a handheld Tesla coil sold as a quack home medical device until about 1940. Said to cure everything from [[carbuncles]] to [[lumbago]]. | width5 = 200 | footer = }} [[File:Tesla D'Arsonval and Oudin electrotherapy circuits.png|thumb|upright=1.8|The three circuits used in electrotherapy apparatus in the early 20th century: (1) Tesla coil, (2) D'Arsonval coil, (3) [[Oudin coil]]. In medical coils for safety ''two'' capacitors ([[Leyden jar]]s) were used, one in each branch of the primary circuit, to completely isolate the patient's body from the potentially lethal currents of the supply transformer, in case of an electrical fault.<ref name="Manders">{{cite journal | last = Manders | first = Horace | title = Some phenomena of high frequency currents | journal = Journal of Physical Therapeutics | volume = 3 | issue = 1 | pages = 220–221 | publisher = John Bale, Sons, and Danielsson, Ltd. | location = London | date = August 1, 1902 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=U75XAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA220&dq=%22P+Oudin | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = December 2, 2014}}</ref> ]]
Tesla had observed as early as 1891 that high frequency currents above 10&nbsp;kHz did not cause the sensation of [[electric shock]], and in fact currents that would be lethal at lower frequencies could be passed through the body without apparent harm.<ref name="McGinley">McGinley, Patton H. "Tesla's contributions to electrotherapy" in {{cite book | last1 = Childress | first1 = David Hatcher, Ed. | title = The Tesla Papers | publisher = Adventures Unlimited Press | date = 2000 | location = | pages = 162–167 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=rwekkS3oD0EC&pg=PA162#v=onepage&q&f=false | doi = | id = | isbn = 0932813860 }}</ref><ref name="Tesla1898">{{cite journal | last1 = Tesla | first1 = Nikola | title = High frequency oscillators for electro-therapeutic and other purposes | journal = The Electrical Engineer | volume = 26 | issue = 550 | pages = 477–481 | publisher = | location = | date = November 17, 1898 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=LOhQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA477 | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = June 10, 2015}} Also read at the 8th annual meeting of The American Electro-Therapeutic Association, Buffalo, New York, Sept. 13-15, 1898</ref><ref name="Rhees">{{cite journal | last1 = Rhees | first1 = David J. | title = Electricity - "The greatest of all doctors": An introduction to "High Frequency Oscillators for Electro-therapeutic and Other Purposes" | journal = Proceedings of the IEEE | volume = 87 | issue = 7 | pages = 1277–1281 | publisher = Inst. of Electrical and Electronic Engineers | location = | date = July 1999 | url = http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/iel5/5/16709/00771078.pdf?arnumber=771078 | issn = | doi = 10.1109/jproc.1999.771078 | id = | accessdate = September 20, 2015}}</ref> He experimented on himself, and claimed daily applications of high voltage relieved [[depression (mood)|depression]].<ref name="Carlson8" >[https://books.google.com/books?id=5I5c9j8BEn4C&pg=PA217 Carlson 2013 ''Tesla: Inventor of the Electrical Age, p. 217]</ref> He was one of the first to observe the heating effect of high frequency currents on the body, the basis of [[diathermy]].<ref name="Kovács">{{cite book | last1 = Kovács | first1 = Richard | title = Electrotherapy and Light Therapy, 5th Ed. | publisher = Lea and Febiger | date = 1945 | location = Philadelphia | pages = 187–188, 197–200 | language = | url = https://archive.org/stream/electrotherapyli00kovrich#page/186/mode/2up | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref><ref name="Cheney2">[https://books.google.com/books?id=HIuK7iLO9zgC&pg=PA103 Cheney (2011) ''Tesla:Man Out of Time'', p. 103]</ref> During his highly publicized early 1890s demonstrations he passed hundreds of thousands of volts through his body.<ref name="Goldman" /><ref name="Carlson2" /> With characteristic hyperbole he called electricity "the greatest of all doctors"<ref name="Carlson8" /> and suggested burying wires under classrooms so its stimulating effect would improve performance of "dull" schoolchildren.<ref name="Cheney2" /><ref name="Gilliams">{{cite journal | last1 = Gilliams | first1 = E. Leslie | title = Tesla's Plan Of Electrically Treating School Children | journal = Popular Electricity | volume = | issue = | pages = 813–814 | publisher = The Popular Electricity Publishing Co. | location = New York | date = December 1912 | url = http://www.teslacollection.com/tesla_articles/1912/popular_electricity_magazine/e_leslie_gilliams/tesla_s_plan_of_electrically_treating_school_children | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = April 30, 2016}}</ref> Tesla wrote two pioneering papers, in 1891<ref name="Saberton">Tesla, N. "High frequency currents for medical purposes" in ''Electrical Engineer'', 1891, cited in Saberton, Claude (1920) ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=swI1AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA131&dq=tesla Diathermy in Medical and Surgical Practice]'', published by Paul B. Hoeber, New York, p. 131</ref> and 1898<ref name="Tesla1898" /><ref name="Rhees" /> on the medical uses of high frequency currents, but did little further work on the subject.
A few other researchers were also experimentally applying high frequency currents to the body at this time.<ref name="Morton">{{cite journal | last1 = Morton | first1 = W. J. | title = A brief glance at electricity in medicine | journal = Transactions of the American Inst. of Electrical Engineers | volume = | issue = | pages = 576–578 | publisher = AIEE | location = New York | date = January 17, 1893 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=yRZKAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA577&dq=tesla+d%27arsonval+thomson | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = September 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Batten">{{cite journal | last1 = Batten | first1 = George B. | title = President's Address | journal = Proc. of the Royal Society of Medicine - Electro-therapeutics section | volume = 20 | issue = 1 | pages = 33–34 | publisher = | location = London | date = October 15, 1926 | url = http://europepmc.org/articles/pmc2100469/pdf/procrsmed01204-0167.pdf | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = September 22, 2015 | pmc=2100469 | pmid=19985436}}</ref><ref name="Williams">{{cite book | last1 = Williams | first1 = Chisolm | title = High Frequency Currents in the Treatment of Some Diseases | publisher = Rebman, Ltd. | date = 1903 | location = London | pages = 8–9 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=GdU0AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA8&dq=tesla+d%27arsonval+Oudin | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref><ref name="Strong" /><ref name="Ho">{{cite book | last1 = Ho | first1 = Mae-Wan | last2 = Popp | first2 = Fritz Albert | last3 = Warnke | first3 = Ulrich | title = Bioelectrodynamics and Biocommunication | publisher = World Scientific | date = 1994 | location = | pages = 10–11 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=uxAfnxKMdPcC&pg=PA10&dq=electrotherapy++diathermy+tesla | doi = | id = | isbn = 9810216653 }}</ref> [[Elihu Thomson]], the co-inventor of the Tesla coil, was one, so in medicine the Tesla coil became known as the "Tesla-Thomson apparatus".<ref name="Strong" /> In France, from 1889 physician and pioneering biophysicist [[Jacques Arsene d'Arsonval|Jacques d'Arsonval]] had been documenting the physiological effects of high frequency current on the body, and had made the same discoveries as Tesla.<ref name="D'Arsonval1893">{{cite journal | last1 = D'Arsonval | first1 = A. | title = Physiological action of currents of great frequency | journal = Modern Medicine and Bacteriological World | volume = 2 | issue = 8 | pages = 200–203 | publisher = Modern Medicine Publishing Co. | location = | date = August 1893 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=yiYCAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA200&dq=%22elihu+thomson%22+tesla | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = November 22, 2015}}, translated by J. H. Kellogg</ref><ref name="Kovács" /><ref name="Ho" /> During his 1892 European trip Tesla met with D'Arsonval and was flattered to find they were using similar circuits. D'Arsonval's spark-excited resonant circuits ''(above)'' did not produce as high voltage as the Tesla transformer.<ref name="Strong" /> In 1893 French physician [[Paul Marie Oudin]] added a "resonator" coil to the D'Arsonval circuit to create the high voltage [[Oudin coil]],<ref name="Ho" /><ref name="JMartin">{{cite book | last1 = Martin | first1 = James M. | title = Practical electro-therapeutics and X-ray therapy | publisher = C.V. Mosby Co. | date = 1912 | location = | pages = | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=1JRYANjbj7IC&pg=PA189&dq=Oudin+coil | doi = | id = | isbn = }}, p.189 fig. 98</ref> a circuit very similar to the Tesla coil, which was widely used for treating patients in Europe.<ref name="Strong" />
During this period, people were fascinated by the new technology of electricity, and many believed it had miraculous curative or "vitalizing" powers.<ref name="Morus">{{cite book | last1 = Morus | first1 = Iwan Rhys | title = Shocking Bodies: Life, Death & Electricity in Victorian England | publisher = The History Press | date = 2011 | location = | pages = 8–11 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=yI4TDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT10&dq=electricity+health+body+revitalizing | doi = | id = | isbn = 0752463810 }}</ref><ref name="Strong1">Strong, Frederick Finch (1908) ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=2S05vCsoKbkC&pg=PA221&dq=%22high+frequency%22+vitalizing High-Frequency Currents]'', p. 220-223</ref><ref name="Peña">{{cite book | last1 = De la Peña | first1 = Carolyn Thomas | title = The Body Electric: How Strange Machines Built the Modern American | publisher = NYU Press | date = 2005 | location = | pages = 98–100 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=MxU8Rf1pKTgC&pg=PA98&dq=electrotherapy | doi = | id = | isbn = 081471983X }}</ref> [[Medical ethics]] were also looser, and doctors could experiment on their patients. By the turn of the century, application of high voltage, "high frequency" currents to the body had become part of a [[Victorian era]] medical field, part legitimate experimental medicine and part [[quack medicine]],<ref name="Rhees" /> called ''[[electrotherapy]]''.<ref name="Peña" /><ref name="Martin">{{cite book | last1 = Martin | first1 = James M. | title = Practical electro-therapeutics and X-ray therapy | publisher = C.V. Mosby Co. | date = 1912 | location = | pages = 187–192 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=1JRYANjbj7IC&pg=PA187&dq=Tesla+D%27Arsonval+Oudin | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref><ref name="Morton1">{{cite journal | last1 = Morton | first1 = William J. | title = Recent advances in electrotherapeutics | journal = The Medical News | volume = 81 | issue = 26 | pages = 1201–1202 | publisher = Lea Brothers and Co. | location = New York | date = December 27, 1902 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=p3AgAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1201&dq=electrotherapy+%22elihu+thomson%22+tesla+oudin+D'arsonval | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = September 5, 2015}}</ref> Manufacturers produced medical apparatus to generate "Tesla currents", "D'Arsonval currents", and "Oudin currents" for physicians. In electrotherapy, a pointed electrode attached to the high voltage terminal of the coil was held near the patient, and the luminous [[brush discharge]]s from it (called "''effluves''") were applied to parts of the body to treat a wide variety of medical conditions. In order to apply the electrode directly to the skin, or tissues inside the mouth, anus or vagina, a "vacuum electrode" was used, consisting of a metal electrode sealed inside a partially evacuated glass tube, which produced a dramatic violet glow. The glass wall of the tube and the skin surface formed a [[capacitor]] which limited the current to the patient, preventing discomfort. These vacuum electrodes were later manufactured with handheld Tesla coils to make "[[violet ray]]" wands, sold to the public as a quack home medical device.<ref name="Behary">{{cite web |last = Behary |first = Jeff |title = Violet Ray Misconceptions |work = The Electrotherapy Museum |publisher = Jeff Behary's website |date = 1997 |url = http://www.electrotherapymuseum.com/Articles/VioletRayMisconceptions.htm |doi = |accessdate = October 13, 2015 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110710181112/http://www.electrotherapymuseum.com/Articles/VioletRayMisconceptions.htm |archivedate = July 10, 2011 |df = }}</ref><ref>The small high voltage coils in these home violet ray wands resembled [[induction coil]]s more than Tesla coils; they had iron core transformers and mechanical interrupters and produced lower voltages, 30&nbsp;-&nbsp;80&nbsp;kV, than Tesla coils</ref>
The popularity of electrotherapy peaked after [[World War 1]],<ref name="Kovács" /><ref name="Peña" /> but by the 1920s authorities began to crack down on fraudulent medical treatments, and electrotherapy largely became obsolete. A part of the field that survived was ''[[diathermy]]'', the application of high frequency current to heat body tissue, pioneered by German physician Karl Nagelschmidt in 1907.<ref name="Kovács" /><ref name="Ho" /> During the 1920s "long wave" (0.5~2&nbsp;MHz) Tesla coil spark diathermy machines were used, in which the current was applied to the body by electrodes. By the 1930s these were being replaced by "short wave" (10~100&nbsp;MHz) vacuum tube diathermy machines,<ref name="Kovács" /><ref name="Ho" /> which had less danger of causing burns, but Tesla coils continued to be used in both diathermy<ref name="Kovács" /> and quack medical devices like [[violet ray]]<ref name="Behary" /> until World War 2. In 1926 [[William T. Bovie]] discovered that RF currents applied to a scalpel could cut and cauterize tissue in medical operations, and spark oscillators were used as [[electrosurgery]] generators or "Bovies" as late as the 1980s.<ref name="Carr">{{cite journal | last1 = Carr | first1 = Joseph J. | title = Early radio transmitters | journal = Popular Electronics | volume = 7 | issue = 5 | pages = 43-46 | publisher = Gernsback Publications | date = May 1990 | url = http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Poptronics/90s/90/PE-1990-03.pdf | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = 21 March 2018}}</ref>
During the 1920s and 30s all unipolar (single terminal) high voltage medical coils came to be called Oudin coils, so today's unipolar Tesla coils are sometimes referred to as "Oudin coils".<ref name="Behary2007">{{cite mailing list | last = Behary | first = Jeff | authorlink = | title = RE: Oudin coil | mailinglist = Tesla Coil Mailing List | date = 1 July 2007 | url = http://www.pupman.com/listarchives/2007/Jul/msg00000.html | accessdate = 16 November 2015}}</ref> {{breakafterimages}}
==Use in show business== {{multiple image | align = center | direction = horizontal | header = | image1 = Electrice sideshow act 1914 - electric chair.jpg | caption1 = "Electrice" sideshow performer being "electrocuted" 1914<ref name="Electrice" /> | width1 = 108 | image2 = Electrice sideshow act 1914 - lighting candle with fingers.jpg | caption2 = "Electrice" lighting a candle with brush discharge from her fingers.<ref name="Electrice" /> The current came from the electric chair she is touching, which is connected to the Tesla coil in the background. | width2 = 269 | image3 = Preacher shooting sparks from fingers 1938.jpg | caption3 = Evangelist Irwin Moon shooting "lightning bolts" from fingers, 1938. | width3 = 96 | image4 = Transtrom's Tesla coil stunts - brush discharge from hand.jpg | caption4 = Demonstrating 10 inch (25 cm) brush discharge from hand, 1913<ref name="Transtrom" /> | width4 = 120 | image5 = Transtrom's Tesla coil stunts - lighting bulb in mouth.jpg | caption5 = RF current from Tesla coil lights the bulb's filament as it passes through the wire to charge and discharge the performer's body, which acts as a capacitor plate.<ref name="Transtrom" /> | width5 = 228 | footer = Turn-of-the-century sideshow performers did stunts with Tesla coils that would be considered extremely dangerous today. '''DON'T TRY THESE''' }}
The Tesla coil's spectacular displays of sparks, and the fact that its currents could pass through the human body without causing [[electric shock]], led to its use in the entertainment business.
In the early 20th century it appeared in [[traveling carnival]]s, [[freak show]]s and circus and carnival [[sideshow]]s, which often had an act in which a performer would pass high voltages through his body<ref name="Goldman">{{cite book | last1 = Goldman | first1 = Harry | title = Kenneth Strickfaden, Dr. Frankenstein's Electrician | publisher = McFarland | date = 2005 | location = | pages = 77–83 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=1FKDBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA77 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0786420642 }}</ref><ref name="Electra">{{cite journal | last1 = "Madamoiselle Electra" | title = How I Give the Public Electric Thrills | journal = Popular Electricity | volume = 4 | issue = 6 | pages = 507–510 | publisher = Popular Electricity Publishing Co. | location = Chicago | date = October 1911 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ELAeAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA508&dq=%22tesla+coil%22+tesla | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = September 25, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Electrice">{{cite journal | last1 = "Electrice" | title = Doing and Daring for the Public's Pleasure | journal = Popular Electricity | volume = 6 | issue = 9 | pages = 1044–1046 | publisher = Popular Electricity Publishing Co. | location = Chicago | date = 1914 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=o5UhAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1044 | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = October 3, 2015}}</ref> <ref name="Gangi">{{cite book | last1 = Gangi | first1 = Tony | title = Carny Sideshows | publisher = Kensington Publishing | date = 2010 | location = | pages = 206 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=qYp5kdbtesIC&pg=PA206 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0806535989 }}</ref><ref name="Nickell">{{cite book | last1 = Nickell | first1 = Joe | title = Secrets of the Sideshows | publisher = University Press of Kentucky | date = 2005 | location = | pages = 248–249 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=p4vQeM0dJAAC&pg=PA248 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0813137373 }}</ref> Performers such as "Dr. Resisto", "The Human Dynamo", "Electrice", "The Great Volta", and "Madamoiselle Electra" would have their body connected to the high voltage terminal of a hidden Tesla coil, causing sparks to shoot from their fingertips and other parts of their body, and [[neon light]]s and [[fluorescent lamp|fluorescent tube lamps]] to light up when brought near them.<ref name="Transtrom">Many of these stunts are demonstrated and explained in {{cite book | last1 = Transtrom | first1 = Henry L. | title = Electricity at high pressures and frequencies | publisher = Joseph G. Branch Publishing Co. | date = 1913 | location = | pages = 189–207 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=1cY3AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA191 | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref><ref name="HFS">{{cite journal | last1 = H.F.S. | title = Electricity in Vaudville | journal = Popular Electricity and the World's Advance | volume = 4 | issue = 1 | pages = 170–171 | publisher = Popular Electricity Publishing Co. | location = New York | date = May 1911 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ELAeAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA170&dq=%22tesla+coil%22+shock | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = 28 September 2017}}</ref><ref name="Bradbury">A lyrical description of such a performer appears in science fiction writer [[Ray Bradbury]]'s 1962 novel {{cite book | title = Something Wicked This Way Comes | publisher = Avon Books | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=oKZVgzIZ0RYC&dq=%22Mr.+Electrico%22 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0062242172 }}. Bradbury has said that this was based on a real performer, Mr. Electrico, part of a seedy traveling carnival, whom he met as a boy in 1932 in Waukegan, Illinois. [http://www.raybradbury.com/inhiswords02.html Bradbury, Ray (December 2001) ''In his words'' blog, Ray Bradbury personal website] and [http://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/6012/the-art-of-fiction-no-203-ray-bradbury Weller, Sam (Spring 2010) "Ray Bradbury interview, The Art of Fiction No. 203", ''The Paris Review'', No. 192, published by Antonio Weiss, New York].</ref> They could also light candles or cigarettes with their fingers.<ref name="Electrice" /> Although they didn't usually cause electric shocks, RF arc discharges from the bare skin could cause painful burns; to prevent them performers sometimes wore metal thimbles on their fingertips<ref name="Electrice" /> ''(Rev. Moon, center image above, is using them)''. These acts were extremely dangerous and could kill the performer if the Tesla coil was misadjusted.<ref name="Gangi" /> In [[carny]] lingo this was called an "electric chair act" because it often included a spark-laced "[[electrocution]]" of the performer in an [[electric chair]],<ref name="Gangi" /><ref name="Nickell" /> exploiting public fascination with this exotic new method of [[capital punishment]], which had become the United States' dominant method of execution around 1900. Today entertainers still perform high voltage acts with Tesla coils,<ref name="Curioddities">Danielle Stamp AKA 'Miss Electra' {{cite book | title = Ripley's Believe It Or Not! Curioddities | publisher = Scholastic, Inc. | date = 2011 | location = | pages = 60–61 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=BObrwFvuqFIC&pg=PA60 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0545316545 }}</ref><ref name="DrMegavolt">{{cite web | last = Richards | first = Austin | title = Dr. Megavolt | work = Personal Website | publisher = High Voltage Entertainment, Inc. | date = 2015 | url = http://drmegavolt.com/ | format = | doi = | accessdate = October 21, 2015}}</ref> but modern [[bioelectromagnetics]] has brought a new awareness of the hazards of Tesla coil currents, and allowing them to pass through the body is today considered extremely dangerous.
Tesla coils were also used as dramatic [[Theatrical property|props]] in early mystery and science fiction [[motion picture]]s, starting in the [[silent era]].<ref name="Goldman" /> The crackling, writhing sparks emanating from the electrode of a giant Tesla coil became Hollywood's iconic symbol of the "[[mad scientist]]'s" lab, recognized throughout the world.<ref name="Skal">{{cite book | last1 = Skal | first1 = David J. | title = Screams of Reason: Mad Science and Modern Culture | publisher = W. W. Norton and Co. | date = 1998 | location = | pages = 89–90 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=m4DiDUvrbqYC&pg=PA89&dq=tesla+%22tesla+coil%22 | doi = | id = | isbn = 039304582X }}</ref> This was probably because the eccentric [[Nikola Tesla]] himself, with his famous high voltage demonstrations and his mysterious Colorado Springs laboratory, was one of the main prototypes from which the "mad scientist" [[stock character]] originated.<ref name="Skal" /><ref name="VanRiper">{{cite book |last=Van Riper |first=A. Bowdoin |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ABtJPIcVtBoC |title=A Biographical Encyclopedia of Scientists and Inventors in American Film and TV since 1930 |year=2011 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |pages=150 |isbn=978-0-8108-8128-0 }}</ref> Some early films in which Tesla coils appeared were ''Wolves of Kultur'' (1918), ''The Power God'' (1926), ''[[Metropolis (1927 film)|Metropolis]]'' (1927), ''[[Frankenstein (1931 film)|Frankenstein]]'' (1931) and its many sequels such as ''[[Son of Frankenstein]]'' (1939), ''[[The Mask of Fu Manchu]]'' (1932), ''[[Chandu the Magician (film)|Chandu the Magician]]'' (1932), ''[[The Lost City (1935 serial)|The Lost City]]'' (1935), and ''[[The Clutching Hand]]'' (1936)<ref name="Tibbetts">William Luddington, "Mr. Electricity: The Multi-Volted Career of Kenneth Strickfaden" in {{cite book | last1 = Tibbetts | first1 = John C. | last2 = Welsh | first2 = James M., Ed. | title = American Classic Screen Profiles | publisher = Scarecrow Press | date = 2010 | location = | pages = 202–208 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=LpcWzZfVEa4C&pg=PA202&lpg=PA202&dq=strickfaden+%22tesla+coil%22 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0810876779 }}</ref><ref name="Goldman" /> and many later films and television shows. By the 1980s, effects like high voltage sparks were being added to movies by [[computer generated imagery|CGI]] as [[visual effects]] in [[post-production]], eliminating the need for dangerous high voltage Tesla coils on sets.
The Tesla coils for many of these movies were constructed by [[Kenneth Strickfaden]] (1896-1984) who, beginning with his spectacular effects in the 1931 ''Frankenstein'', became Hollywood's preeminent electrical [[special effects]] expert.<ref name="Goldman" /><ref name="Hanson">{{cite journal | last1 = Hanson | first1 = Eugene M. | title = High-Voltage Magic | journal = Popular Mechanics | volume = 92 | issue = 3 | pages = 140–142 | publisher = The Popular Mechanics Co. | location = Chicago, USA | date = September 1949 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=6tgDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA140&lpg=PA140&dq=Tesla | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = October 1, 2015}}</ref> His large "Meg Senior" Tesla coil seen in many of these movies consisted of a 6-foot 1000 turn conical secondary and a 10 turn primary, connected to a capacitor through a rotary spark gap, powered by a 20&nbsp;kV transformer.<ref name="Hanson" /> It could produce 6 foot sparks. Some of his last gigs were the reassembly of the original 1931 ''Frankenstein'' high voltage apparatus for the Mel Brooks satire ''[[Young Frankenstein]]'' (1974), and construction of a million volt Tesla coil which produced 12 foot sparks for a 1976 stage show by the rock band ''[[Kiss (band)|Kiss]]''.<ref name="Tibbetts" /> {{breakafterimages}}
== Use in education == {{multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal | header = | image1 = Tesla coil at Griffith Observatory LA.jpg | caption1 = Million volt [[Griffith Park Observatory]] coil, Los Angeles. Over 100 years old, it is one of the oldest working Tesla coils. | width1 = 167 | image2 = High frequency inductance experiment 1906.jpg | caption2 = Demonstration of inductance with a Tesla coil, 1906.<ref name="Collins">{{cite journal | last1 = Collins | first1 = Archie Frederick | title = High-Potential Discharges | journal = Scientific American | volume = 94 | issue = 4 | pages = 92–93 | publisher = Munn and Co. | location = New York | date = January 27, 1906 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=nqMzAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA92 | issn = | doi = 10.1038/scientificamerican01271906-92 | id = | accessdate = December 15, 2016}}</ref> RF current will not pass through the heavy copper wire because of the bend, and passes through the lamp instead. | width2 = 140 }} [[File:Small Tesla coil kit 1918.jpg|thumb|Small educational Tesla coil kit, 1918]]
Ever since Tesla's 1890s lectures, Tesla coils have been used as attractions in educational exhibits and [[science fair]]s. They have become a way to counter the stereotype that science is boring.<ref name="Goldman2" /> In the early 20th century, experts like [[Henry Transtrom]] and [[Earle Ovington]] gave high voltage demonstrations at "electric fairs".<ref name="Transtrom" /> High school classes built Tesla coils.
From 1933 into the 1980s, between movie jobs Hollywood special effects expert [[Kenneth Strickfaden|Ken Strickfaden]] would take his high voltage apparatus on the road in an exhibition called "Science on Parade" and later "The Kenstric Space Age Science Show" to high schools, colleges, World Fairs and expositions.<ref name="Goldman2">[https://books.google.com/books?id=_xkZIjk3lXAC&pg=PA66 Goldman (2005) ''Kenneth Strickfaden, Dr. Frankenstein's Electrician'', p. 62-68]</ref> These spectacular shows, which reached 48 states, had a seminal influence on the birth of the modern "coiling" movement.<ref name="Tibbetts" /> A number of present-day Tesla hobbyists such as William Wysock say they were inspired to build Tesla coils by seeing Strickfaden's show.<ref name="Goldman2" />
One of the oldest and best-known coils still in operation is the "GPO-1" at [[Griffith Park Observatory]] in Los Angeles. It was originally one of a pair of coils built in 1910 by [[Earle L. Ovington]], a friend of Tesla and manufacturer of high voltage electrotherapy apparatus.<ref name="Gurstelle">{{cite book | last1 = Gurstelle | first1 = William | title = Adventures from the Technology Underground | publisher = Crown/Archetype | date = 2009 | location = | pages = 71–73 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=EUvh6Z2MzuAC&pg=PA72&dq=%22tesla+coil%22 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0307510654 }}</ref><ref name="Triposo">{{cite web | title = Griffith Observatory | work = Destinations | publisher = Triposo Travel Guide | date = 2015 | url = https://www.triposo.com/poi/N__224245857 | format = | doi = | accessdate = April 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name="Goldman"/> For a number of years Ovington displayed them at the December electrical trade show at [[Madison Square Garden]] in New York City, using them for demonstrations of high voltage science, which Tesla himself sometimes attended.<ref name="Goldman"/> Called the ''Million Volt Oscillator'', the twin coils were installed on the balcony at the show. Every hour the lights were dimmed and the public was treated to a display of 10 foot arcs.<ref name="Triposo" /> Ovington gave the coils to his friend Dr. [[Frederick Finch Strong]], a leading figure in the alternative health field of [[electrotherapy]]. In 1937 Strong donated the coils to the Griffith Observatory. The museum didn't have room to display both, but one coil was restored by Kenneth Strickfaden and has been in daily operation ever since.<ref name="Goldman"/> It consists of a 48 in. (1.2 m) high conical secondary coil topped by a 12 in. (30&nbsp;cm) diameter copper ball electrode, with a 9-turn spiral primary of 2 in. copper strip, a glass plate capacitor (replacing the original Leyden jars), and rotary spark gap.<ref name="Gurstelle" /> Its output has been estimated at 1.3 million volts.<ref name="Triposo" /> {{breakafterimages}}
==Later uses== [[File:Tuve & Breit Tesla coil particle accelerator 1928.jpg|thumb|Breit and Tuve's 5 MV Tesla coil used as particle accelerator, 1928]]
In addition to its use in [[spark-gap transmitter|spark-gap radio transmitters]] and [[electrotherapy]] described above, the Tesla coil circuit was also used in the early 20th century in [[x-ray machine]]s, [[ozone generator]]s for water purification, and [[induction heating]] equipment. However, in the 1920s [[vacuum tube]] [[electronic oscillator|oscillators]] replaced it in all these applications.<ref name="Tilbury1" /> The [[triode]] vacuum tube was a much better radio frequency current generator than the noisy, hot, [[ozone]]-producing spark, and could produce [[continuous wave]]s. After this, industrial use of the Tesla coil was mainly limited to a few specialized applications which were suited to its unique characteristics, such as high voltage insulation testing.
In 1926, pioneering accelerator physicists [[Merle Tuve]] and [[Gregory Breit]] built a 5 million volt Tesla coil as a linear [[particle accelerator]].<ref name="Breit">{{cite journal | last1 = Breit | first1 = G. M. | last2 = Tuve | first2 = M. A. | last3 = Dahl | first3 = O. | title = A laboratory method of producing high potentials | journal = Physical Review | volume = 35 | issue = | pages = 51–65 | publisher = AIP | location = | date = January 1930 | url = | issn = | doi = 10.1103/physrev.35.51 | id = | accessdate = }}</ref><ref name="Armagnac">{{cite journal | last1 = Armagnac | first1 = Alden P. | title = A five-million-volt gun built to smash atoms | journal = Popular Science | volume = 114 | issue = 1 | pages = 23–24 | publisher = Popular Science Publishing Co. | location = New York | date = January 1929 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=oCcDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA23 | issn = 0161-7370 | doi = | id = | accessdate = September 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Heilbron">{{cite book | last1 = Heilbron | first1 = J. L. | last2 = Seidel | first2 = Robert W. | title = Lawrence and His Laboratory: A History of the Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory, Vol. 1 | publisher = Univ. of California Press | date = 1989 | location = | pages = 53–54, 58–59 | language = | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=vtMoJ63k6SUC&pg=PA53&dq=%22Tesla+coil%22 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0520064267 }}</ref> The bipolar coil consisted of a pyrex tube a meter long wound with 8000 turns of fine wire, with round corona caps on each end, and a 5 turn spiral primary coil surrounding it at the center. It was operated in a tank of insulating oil pressurized to 500 psi which allowed it to reach a potential of 5.2 megavolts. Although it was used for a short period in 1929-30 it was not a success because the particles' acceleration had to be completed within the brief period of a half cycle of the RF voltage.
In 1970 Robert K. Golka built a replica of Tesla's huge Colorado Springs magnifying transmitter in a shed at [[Wendover Air Force Base]], Utah, using data he found in Tesla's lab notes archived at the [[Nikola Tesla Museum]] in [[Beograd]], Serbia.<ref name="Shunamen" /><ref name="Golka">{{cite journal | last1 = Golka | first1 = Robert K. | title = Project Tesla - In Search of an Answer to Our Energy Needs | journal = Radio-Electronics | volume = 52 | issue = 2 | pages = 47–49 | publisher = Gernsback Publications, Inc. | location = New York | date = February 1981 | url = http://www.teslauniverse.com/nikola-tesla/articles/project-tesla-search-answer-our-energy-needs | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = September 4, 2015}}</ref> <ref name="Lawren">{{cite journal | last1 = Lawren | first1 = Bill | title = Rediscovering Tesla | journal = Omni Magazine | volume = 10 | issue = 6 | pages = 64–66, 68, 116–117 | publisher = | location = | date = March 1988 | url = http://www.teslauniverse.com/nikola-tesla/articles/rediscovering-tesla | issn = | doi = | id = | accessdate = September 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name="Reed">{{cite journal | last1 = Reed | first1 = John Randolph | title = Designing high-gain triple resonant Tesla transformers | version = | publisher = Dept. of Engineering and Computer Science, Univ. of Central Florida | date = 2000 | url = http://hotstreamer.deanostoybox.com/DesigningtripleresonanceTeslatransformers.pdf | format = PDF | accessdate = August 2, 2015}}</ref> This was one of the first experiments with the magnifier circuit since Tesla's time. The coil generated 12 million volts. Golka used it to try to duplicate Tesla's reported synthesis of [[ball lightning]].
